s the correct team_id and task_id\n\n### Scenario 8: Credential resolution (`tests/credential_resolution.rs`)\n\n1. Setup: create user with sink credentials (insert directly into DB: encrypted access_token for the local git repo) and LLM API key (insert encrypted mock key)\n2. Create team, inbox, submit task as the user\n3. Wait for task to complete (timeout: 60s)\n4. Verify:\n   - The mock agent ran successfully (which means credentials were resolved and passed to the Host Wrapper)\n   - The commit was pushed to the sink repo (which means sink credentials worked)\n\n### Scenario 9: Service principal submission (`tests/service_principal.rs`)\n\n1. Setup: create admin user with credentials, create service principal with `credential_source_user_id` pointing to the admin\n2. Create team, add SP as collaborator, create inbox\n3. Submit task as the service principal (using SP API token)\n4. Wait for task to complete (timeout: 60s)\n5. Verify:\n   - Task's submitting_entity_type is ServicePrincipal\n   - Credentials were resolved from the linked admin user\n   - Task completed successfully\n\n### Scenario 10: Job directory cleanup (`tests/job_dir_cleanup.rs`)\n\n1. Setup: team with inbox, configure short cleanup grace period for testing (if possible via env var override, or accept the default and check immediate cleanup for succeeded jobs)\n2. Submit a task, wait for completion\n3. After job succeeds:\n   - Verify the job directory no longer exists (succeeded jobs are cleaned up immediately after commit/push)\n4. Submit another task configured to fail (mock agent fail mode, retry_count=0 so it dead-letters immediately)\n5. After job fails:\n   - Verify the job directory still exists (retained for grace period)\n   - Wait for grace period to expire (or verify it's scheduled for cleanup)\n\n## Dependencies\n\n- Task 13 (Scheduler — must be functional for agent instances to run)\n- Task 14 (Host Wrapper — must be functional)\n- Task 15 (MCP Server — must be functional)\n- Task 16 (Mock Agent — used as the LLM Host replacement)\n- Task 17 (Docker Compose and ci-instance.sh — test infrastructure)\n- Tasks 06-11 (all API endpoints must be implemented)\n\n## Testing Requirements\n\nThese ARE the tests. The deliverable of this task is the test suite itself. Each scenario is a test. The testing requirements below describe how to verify the test infrastructure works:\n\n### Test infrastructure verification\n\n- The test crate compiles: `cargo build -p vertical-tests`\n- The test helper can connect to a running test instance and create a test admin user\n- The test helper can create a local bare git repo for use as a sink\n- The SSE stream helper correctly parses SSE events from the platform\n\n### CI integration\n\n- All 10 scenarios pass when run against a Docker Compose test instance: `scripts/ci-instance.sh up 1 && cargo nextest run -p vertical-tests -- --test-threads=1 && scripts/ci-instance.sh down 1`\n- Tests run sequentially (`--test-threads=1`) to avoid resource contention and simplify debugging\n- Each test cleans up its own resources (teams, tasks, sink repos) to avoid state leakage between tests\n- Test timeout: each scenario has a maximum runtime (60-120s) after which it fails with a clear timeout message\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n1. All 10 vertical slice test scenarios are implemented and pass against a running Docker Compose test instance.\n2. Tests exercise the full stack: API -> Scheduler -> Host Wrapper -> MCP Server -> Mock Agent -> back to API.\n3. The single-task completion scenario validates the complete happy path from task submission to commit in the sink repo.\n4. The multi-stage pipeline scenario validates child task creation and chaining across 3 inboxes.\n5. Failure and retry scenarios validate the retry state machine and dead-letter queue.\n6. Concurrency tests validate the FIFO dequeuing and per-team cap enforcement.\n7. SSE tests validate real-time event delivery to connected clients.\n8. Credential resolution