rectory on each invocation—if it doesn't exist on the first call, create it and fail; on retry, the signal file exists so it can complete successfully. I need to re-examine the retry scenario more carefully—the spec says the mock agent should check for a signal file on first invocation, create it and fail, then on retry the file exists so it completes. Since retries use the same root_task_id, the job directory should persist across invocations, making this approach viable. These are vertical slice tests running against a real system, so I need to think through how the actual scheduler handles retries.\n\nThe real constraint is that I can't modify mock agent environment variables per task in the vertical tests—the agent runs inside Docker and the tests are external HTTP clients. Instead, I need to have the mock agent parse its behavior from the agent prompt itself, which the test can control per task. The spec already calls for parsing MOCK_CONFIG directives from the agent prompt, so I'll have the mock agent extract configuration like mode overrides and child inbox settings directly from those prompt lines.\n\nFor the retry scenario specifically, the mock agent will check the agent prompt for the signal file directive, fail on the first attempt, then succeed on retry once the signal file appears. I could also have the mock agent check the task body for overrides instead, but parsing the agent prompt is cleaner since that's what the spec already suggests.\n\nNow I'm thinking through what the vertical tests actually need to work: direct database access for setting up users and credentials, JWT token generation using the same key as the API server, a local git repository to act as a sink, and the ability to parse SSE streams. The database should be accessible through the exposed port in the test docker-compose, but getting the JWT signing key is trickier since it's generated during CI setup and injected into the container.\n\nLooking at how ci-instance.sh works, it generates the keys and exports them as environment variables, so if the test crate reads those same variables, it can sign tokens and encrypt credentials the same way the API server does. This means the flow is straightforward: the keys get generated once, exported as env vars, used by both the Docker container and the test crate.\n\nNow I'm mapping out the structure I need to build: a test utilities crate with a TestClient, error handling, SSE stream parsing, and a test sink repository, plus the actual vertical test files.\n\nI also need to update the workspace Cargo.toml to include the new crate and modify the mock agent's config to support prompt-based configuration.\n\nNow I'm examining the mock agent source to understand the exact structure before implementing the changes for parsing config from the prompt and handling conditional failures with signal files.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":10705,"cache_read_input_tokens":53156,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":10705},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"281ffad8-1750-48bf-9df8-885c78e7fc19","uuid":"b93c271c-0994-49be-aa92-3d5b9e9c528f"}
